The following section summarizes the traffic impact analysis for the proposed South Pond
Village development in the City of Ann Arbor, Michigan. The South Pond Village project is
located on a vacant parcel of land lying north of the Arborland Shopping Center near the
interchange between US 23 and M-17, US-23 BR, I-94 BL (Washtenaw Avenue). The site is in
the easternmost part of the city adjacent to Pittsfield Township.
The South Pond Village project would involve the construction of 76 single family homes on
the site with access to Chalmers Drive through the Woodcreek residential subdivision. South
Pond Village’s primary access connection would be a drive that runs along the southern edge of
the Woodcreek subdivision and connects to Woodcreek Boulevard. The secondary access
point would tie into the subdivision through Algebe Way which connects to Woodcreek
The approximately 85% of the South Pond Village traffic is assumed to come from and head
toward the south, towards the intersection of Washtenaw Avenue and Chalmers Drive. The
rest of the site traffic is assumed to travel to and from the north towards Huron River Drive.
No road improvements or signal timing changes are necessary to accommodate the traffic
generated by the South Pond Village project.
The following section summarizes the traffic analyses for the proposed South Pond Village
development in the City of Ann Arbor, Michigan. The South Pond Village project is located
north of the existing Arborland Shopping Center near the interchange with US 23 and
Washtenaw Avenue in the east portion of the City of Ann Arbor. Figure 2-1 provides a location
area map pertaining to the project site.
The study area includes the following three intersections:
Washtenaw Avenue is a paved five lane business route under the jurisdiction of the Michigan
Department of Transportation (MDOT). Near Chalmers Drive, the posted speed limit is 40
mph and there are two through lanes in each direction with a center left-turn lane. A short
distance to the east of Chalmers, the center left-turn lane changes to a filled concrete median to
prevent eastbound left-turns from Washtenaw into the one-way outbound Arborland Driveway
at Pittsfield Boulevard. Left turning vehicles from Chalmers Drive often make two-stage turns,
first into the short center-left turn lane section, then merging into eastbound Washtenaw
Avenue traffic when clear. The Chalmers Drive approach is controlled with a stop sign.
Chalmers Drive and Pittsfield Boulevard are under the jurisdiction of the City of Ann Arbor.
Chalmers Drive is a two-land gravel roadway with a posted speed limit of 25 mph. It serves the
Woodcreek residential development that lies north of the Arborland Shopping Center and west
of the proposed South Pond Village site. Pittsfield Boulevard serves the residential areas to the
south of Washtenaw Avenue and has a posted speed limit of 25 mph. Pittsfield Boulevard is
aligned across from the westernmost Arborland exit only drive and is controlled by a traffic

page.text: The subject site is a vacant, 48 acre parcel bordered by US-23 (exit ramp to Washtenaw
Avenue) to the east; Arborland Mall to the south; Woodcreek Condominium development to
the west; and Huron River Drive to the north.
Vehicular access to the site is critical. No ingress/egress can originate from the east property
line due to US-23. Direct access to Huron River Drive would prove too much of a negative
impact on the existing wetland and to the Mallett's Creek corridor. South Pond Village
connects through the Woodcreek subdivision through Algebe Way and through Woodcreek
Boulevard along the southern edge of the Woodcreek subdivision.
Figure 2-3 shows the proposed site plan for the development.

page.text: There are two (2) access points proposed for the South Pond Village Project. The site plan,
illustrated back on Figure 2-3, shows the location of the two access points that connect the
South Pond Village development to Chalmers Drive through the Woodcreek subdivision.
From Chalmers Drive, residents can come from and travel to either Huron River Drive to the
north, or Washtenaw Avenue to the south.
The comparison, in section 3.0 above, between the peak hour traffic volumes in 2008 and the
existing traffic volumes taken in July 2014 suggests that there has not been any significant
increase or decrease in traffic volumes over the past six (6) years. We are not aware of any
proposed developments or other changes in conditions which affect traffic volumes. Therefore,
it is assumed for the purposes of this traffic study, that traffic volumes will remain steady over
the next several years and no background growth factors will be applied to the existing 2014
volumes. The forecast traffic volumes will be the simple summation of the existing 2014 traffic
volumes plus the site-generated traffic volumes from South Pond Village.

The new trips associated with South Pond Village are distributed to the street system according
to the approximate directional distributions observed during each of the peak traffic periods.
The percentages of traffic distributed in each direction are as follows:
• 15% to and from the north on Chalmers Drive towards Huron River Drive
• 50% to and from the west on Washtenaw Avenue
• 35% to and from the east on Washtenaw Avenue

page.text: Capacity analysis for this traffic study is done utilizing the Synchro/SimTraffic program to create a
traffic model of the existing and forecast traffic scenarios. Each scenario is run approximately 10 times
to generate average delays at each of the study intersections. While the average delay per vehicle
calculated in the SimTraffic model is not calculated utilizing the same methodology as the Highway
Capacity Manual, the Level-of-Service (LOS) grades will be assigned to each intersection with the same
range of average delays for signalized and signalized intersections as the Highway Capacity Manual.
The Highway Capacity Manual assigns the following level-of-service grades to the ranges of control
delay in seconds for unsignalized and signalized intersections. Generally LOS D is considered the limit
LOS A B C D E
LOS A B C D E

Since the capacity analysis is as average of 10 randomized runs, a standard deviation in results
will occur. Due to this standard deviation in runs, forecast models with higher traffic volumes
may actually have less calculated delay for a turning movement, particularly in situations where
longer queues and delays fluctuate on a run by run basis.

The signalized intersection of Washtenaw Avenue and Pittsfield currently operates at an overall
level of service A during the morning peak hour. The average level of service during the
existing afternoon peak hour is a C. The average delays and queues are not expected to
significantly change with the addition of the South Pond Village traffic during the forecast peak
There are occasions, during the morning peak hour, when traffic backups from Washtenaw and
Huron Parkway reduce the westbound traffic flow through this intersection.
Given the light traffic volumes on Chalmers Drive, there is very little delay for vehicles that
turn into and out of Woodcreek Boulevard during the existing or forecast peak hours of the
day. All turning movements operate at a level of service A.
Since the speed limit is 25 miles per hour and the traffic volumes on Chalmers are very light, no
left-turn passing or right-turn deceleration lanes are necessary at this intersection to provide
safe and efficient access for the additional traffic volumes from South Pond Village.
Eastbound traffic during the existing afternoon peak hour and westbound traffic during both
the morning and afternoon peak hours occasionally backup past this intersection. This existing
traffic condition makes it more difficult to turn into and out of Chalmers Drive.
Traffic that turns left from Chalmers to eastbound Washtenaw regularly use the short center
left-turn lane median as a shelter to complete the left turn in two stages. Right turning traffic
either waits for a gap in westbound traffic or is let in by other drivers if traffic is backed up pas
Even though there are heavy traffic volumes and long queues on Washtenaw at this
intersection, existing queues on Chalmers were observed to be short. The additional traffic
from the South Pond Village project is expected to increase the queues on southbound
Chalmers by a car length and increase the average delays by a small amount.
Despite the increased delays and queues, a separate left-turn and right-turn lane for the
Chalmers approach is not recommended at this time, since any small reduction in average
delays would likely be outweighed by increased accident potential caused by drivers that are side
by side and are impairing each other’s sight distance at an intersection.
Despite the existing heavy traffic volumes and queuing along Washtenaw Avenue near Chalmers Drive,
the South Pond Village project would only increase peak hour traffic by a relatively small amount and
not significantly impact the traffic operations along Washtenaw Avenue.
Traffic currently can and will continue to be able to enter and exit Chalmers Drive even with the slight
additional traffic from the South Pond Village project. In times of very heavy congestion, South Pond
